ere are no runtime processing logs showing successful IPv4 LPM lookups for received packets from switch_1, which is consistent with the parser misalignment: hdr.ipv4.dstAddr would not match real destinations, leading to table misses and default drop.\n  - Additional observation: Intermittent inability to connect to the thrift client on port 9090 was observed for switch_2, though it later reports starting the thrift server. This may complicate control-plane introspection but is not required to explain the data-plane failure.\n\nBloom filter logic note\n- The Bloom filter update is only triggered for TCP packets. ICMP (used by ping) does not invoke the update or the drop threshold logic. Therefore, the Bloom filter is not implicated in the current ping failure.\n\nAnomalies detected\n1) Critical: switch_2 P4 program has an incorrect IPv4 header layout (identification declared as bit<6> instead of bit<16>). This will corrupt IPv4 parsing and consequently the LPM key (dstAddr), producing table misses and drops.\n2) Secondary: Occasional thrift connectivity issues reported for switch_2 (“Could not connect to thrift client on port 9090”), which impeded some queries but are not the primary cause of the forwarding failure.\n3) Non-blocking but unusual: The ipv4_forward action sets ethernet.srcAddr = ethernet.dstAddr before setting the destination MAC. This results in frames whose source MAC may equal the destination MAC. While odd, this is not required to explain the observed failure given item (1).\n\nFault localization\n- The forwarding failure localizes to switch_2’s ingress pipeline parsing of IPv4 headers and subsequent LPM match. switch_1 forwards traffic correctly to switch_2; the packets likely get dropped at switch_2 due to an LPM miss caused by header misparsing.\n\nRoot cause\n- Mismatched/incorrect P4 program on switch_2: the malformed IPv4 header definition (identification field sized as bit<6>) misaligns subsequent fields, causing the dstAddr used for LPM lookup to be incorrect. This leads to default drop behavior in switch_2’s IPv4 LPM table and end-to-end connectivity failure.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17578, "output_tokens": 5440, "total_tokens": 23018, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16512}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4416}}}
